node.title: Unclear whether Medsafe to analyse vaccine data for kids over Christmas break
node.description: But experts say it's prudent to wait for more information before making a decision on vaccine approval for a population group where the chances of severe illness are slim.

node.title: Biden visits Coast Guard on Thanksgiving
node.description: President Biden and his family are spending Thanksgiving on Nantucket island.

node.title: EU Advises Member Countries to Not Enact Tighter COVID Restrictions, Over Travel Concerns
node.description: In hopes of saving free travel between the nation-bloc's 27 countries, the EU is recommending countries against implementing restrictions amid the latest surge.

node.title: 'They stop women from having dreams': Arezo is speaking out, something forbidden in her homeland
node.description: Exam pressure in Year 12 can be hard enough, but Hobart student Arezo Hami has had the added layer of negotiating help for Afghan family members coping with life under the Taliban.

node.title: How First Nations footballer Kyah Simon found her voice
node.description: The Indigenous Matilda only learned about the extent of her family history as an adult, but is now using her knowledge and the wider Black Lives Matter movement to speak out on issues of racism and discrimination.

node.title: Efat couldn't say goodbye to her family when she fled Kabul. Now she doesn't know if she'll see them again
node.description: Recently evacuated Afghans are pleading with the federal government to prioritise their families' visa applications because of their connections to Australia, amid concerns they could be targeted by the Taliban.

node.title: The world is asking 'Where is Peng Shuai?', but Chinese tennis fans don't even know she's missing
node.description: Even China's biggest tennis fans haven't heard about Peng Shuai's alleged disappearance, which is causing alarm among international tennis players and human rights groups.

node.title: 'I couldn't find a job to save my life': Prue spent three years looking for work before starting her own law firm
node.description: Australians with a disability have a much lower level of workforce participation than those without, with many locked out of job opportunities by prejudice. There's a growing body of evidence that suggests this is not just bad for them, but bad for business profits and the economy.

node.title: It’s been called 'the devil's machine’. Macquarie Bank used a more technical name for it
node.description: Internal documents show how Australia's largest investment bank took part in a controversial German tax scheme despite warnings of reputational damage and legal risk.

node.title: A new generation challenges Morrison amid a chaotic week full of revolts
node.description: Within the shambles, there has actually been one encouraging sign. We're seeing a new generation of Liberal moderates belatedly raise their voices, writes Michelle Grattan.

node.title: NASA moves ahead with December launch for Hubble successor

node.title: ‘Licorice Pizza’ Review: California Dreaming and Scheming

node.title: These slivers of carved mammoth tusk may be ancient jewellery — or something else entirely
node.description: A beautiful ivory artefact is the oldest example of decorated jewellery in Eurasia,  international archaeologists say. But could it be something even more intriguing?

node.title: Happiness is being able to afford a surprise vet bill
node.description: Money may not be able to buy happiness but recent research shows it helps. But the income needed for a happy life is increasingly out-of-reach for ordinary Australians.
